Introduction

What is survival analysis and how is it different from other types of analysis? Survival analysis Survival analysis focuses on time until an event occurs. This event (represented by a categorical variable typically) is a qualitative change that is tied to a specific point in time. Survival analysis was originally designed for medical studies and the occurrence of death - hence the name. However, many more fields are interested in survival analysis. Other names that people use to describe survival analysis are time-to-event analysis, duration analysis, and failure analysis.

This markdown file contains information on how to perform survival analysis and all of its components in SAS and R. In each section you are able to toggle back and forth between the code and output you desire to view.

The first thing that we need to do is load up all of the needed libraries in R that we will be using. This isn’t needed for the SAS sections of the code.

install.packages("survival")
install.packages("survminer")
install.packages("flexsurv")
install.packages("visreg")
install.packages("ggplot2")
install.packages("MASS")

library(survival)
library(survminer)

Censoring, Survival, and Hazards

In survival analysis, the target variable is actually two pieces - one continuous and one categorical:

  1. Time: tenure for an observation (continuous)
  2. Event/status: at the end of that time, what happened? (categorical)

Survival analysis has a target variable that is typically broken into two pieces - occurrence of an event and time until the event. Here, “time” generally refers to tenure rather than actual calendar time. The “event” is some specific outcome of interest such as a customer cancelling service, a customer making another purchase, a patient developing a disease, or a customer defaulting on a loan. Unlike classification models (logistic regression for example) that just focus on whether an event happened, survival analysis also desires to understand how long before the event happened if the event happened at all.

One might think that we then have a typical continuous target variable problem and linear regression with ordinary least squares (OLS) would suffice. However, the biggest problem with using OLS for time-to-event data is that not all observations have experienced the event. This is called censoring. Another problem with traditional OLS regression is that tenure must always be positive which makes satisfying the normality assumption of the residuals difficult. Also, the risk of failure (not surviving) could easily change across time, which OLS cannot account for. Instead, you can imagine survival analysis as a classification problem predicting probability of an event across time.

We will be using a Maryland recidivism data set from a study done in the 1970’s to model the association between various factors and the length of time before the possible event of rearrest within one year. Of the 432 men in the study, 114 of them were rearrested within one year. The variables in the data set are the following:

Maryland Recidivism Data Dictionary

Time & Censoring

Survival analysis has a few things that set it apart from any other statistical modeling approaches:

  • Time to an event
  • Censoring

Just like most models, survival analysis depends on certain assumptions. One of the big assumptions is defining when time starts. In survival analysis, we create an artificial world in which everyone “starts” at the same time. This goes back to our interest in tenure instead of time. These are both compared in the following figure:

Time vs. Tenure

This choice of a starting point in time isn’t always obvious. Here are some examples of this problem from different fields:

  • Time since exposure to disease vs. developing the disease for medical studies
  • Time since diagnosis vs. surgery vs. treatment for hospital readmissions or recovery
  • Time since a previous or different event
  • Time until car breaks from production vs. purchase vs. last repair

Interested in time to event \(T\), but we can not observe this for all observations since not all observations have had or even won’t ever have the event. These observations are called censored. The tenure we actually observe for each observation i is the minimum between the time to the event (\(T_i\)) or the censoring time (\(C_i\)). The corresponding categorical variable informs us which one of these we observe for each observation.

However, a censored observation is not a missing observation. We do not know the actual time \(T_i\) for the censored observations, but we do know that for some amount of time - namely \(C_i\) - the event has not occurred. This provides some but not all information about \(T-i\). Censoring data is incomplete rather than missing. Ignoring censored observations would be falsely acting as if we know nothing about \(T_i\).

There are different variations of censoring. First let’s talk about Type I vs. Type II censoring.

  • Type I (most common): there is a specific end time \(c\), and any subject that hasn’t had the event by time \(c\) is censored
  • Type II: time goes until a certain (pre-specified) number of events have occurred, and any subjects who haven’t had the event by that time are censored

While Type I vs. Tyype II censoring is one distinction for censoring, another distinction is right, left, or interval censoring.

  • Right (most common): the event time \(T_i > c\)
    • Example: Customer has monthly subscription for at least 3 months
  • Left: the event time \(T_i < c\)
    • Example: Patient joined a medical study after already having the disease
  • Interval: the event time is between two bounds \(a < T_i < b\)
    • Example: Person tests negative during appointment at \(a\), but positive during appointment at \(b\) so disease was developed in between

The last distinction for censoring involves an assumption around independence. First, we must distinguish between fixed and random censoring.

  • Fixed: censoring only occurs at the end of the study (\(C_i = c\) is known in advance)
    • Example: Not arrested in 52 weeks is censored by design as that is when the study ended
  • Random: censoring time \(C_i\) may vary between subjects for reasons beyond the investigator’s control
    • Example: Not arrested within first 30 weeks, but left study for unknown reason

Typically, we assume the the event time \(T_i\) and the censoring time \(C_i\) are independent. That implies that subjects censored at time \(t\) were randomly selected to be censored from all subjects still in the risk set at that time. If this is true, then there is no mathematical difference between random and fixed censoring as defined above. However, if that assumption is not true, then there is a difference between fixed and random censoring that needs to be accounted for. These are dealt with in the section on competing risks.

Survival Function

When it comes to survival data we are interested in the event time \(T\). There are some unique challenges to summarizing information about \(T\). We know that \(T\) is bounded at zero and most likely right skewed. That means that variances and averages are not the best form of summarizing. When censoring is present, are averages and variances aren’t even as meaningful since we don’t fully know all the values of \(T\). Instead, we focus on two typical functions to summarize survival data - the survival function and the hazard function.

The survival function is the probability of surviving beyond time \(t\):

\[ S(t) = P(T>t) \] This function always starts at 1 (or 100%) when the time equals 0 and bounded below by 0. This function also never increases as once observations have had the event, they are no longer considered as survived. These curves are the foundation of the field of survival analysis.

The Kaplan-Meier (KM) method is the primary way we estimate survival functions. We want to estimate the proportion of observations that have yet to experience the event at any given time \(t\). The KM method calculates the survival function as follows:

\[ \hat{S}(t) = \Pi_{k \le t} (1 - \frac{d_{k}}{r_{k}}) \] In the above equation, \(d_{k}\) is the number of events occurring at time \(t\), while \(r_{k}\) is the number of observations “at risk” of having the event right before time \(t\). The KM method has actually existed long before Kaplan and Meier, but Kaplan and Meier showed it was the maximum likelihood estimate for the nonparametric estimation of the survival curve.

Let’s see how to produce these in each of our softwares using the simple data set we have in the picture below. Then we will use our prisoner recidivism data set.

Time vs. Tenure

SAS

Let’s look at the survival function for the above visualized data set of six customers. Customers C and F were censored, while customers A, B, D, and E had the events.

We have created those six observations using the DATA step below. PROC LIFETEST is then used to calculate the survival curve. The data = option specifies the data set we are using. The time statement specifies the two pieces of our target variable that we are mapping the survival curve for. The first piece is the time (or tenure) component called Tenure in our data set. The next piece is the variable flagging censored observations called censored in our data set. The value in the parantheses signifies the observations that are censored. Note that this is different than R which specifies the observations that are not censored.

SAS will provide a table listing all of the values in the survival curve. Since our data set only has six observations, this is rather small. However, be careful with large datasets as this table can grow rather quickly. At time 0, we can see that the survival curve equals 1 since all observations have not had the event at time zero. At time 2, our first observation (E) has the event, dropping the survival function to 0.8333. At time 3 we have a couple of things happening. First, we have another observation (D) with the event so our survival curve drops to 0.6667. However, F is censored at this time point. That does mean that F didn’t have the event at time 3, but isn’t around until time 4 so although our number of events stays at 2, the number at risk drops from 4 to 3 since F is no longer at risk right after time 3. Times 7 and 8 also see drops in the survival function since observations A and B had the events at those times respectively. Lastly, observation C is censored at time point 10 which means that the number at risk is now 0 which stops the calculation of the survival curve.

SAS also provides some summary statistics around our data too. It provides the quartiles as well as the mean. As mentioned above, the mean isn’t as valuable here since we have censored observations. However, the median is still valid as long as the event occurs for more than half of the sample. This point on the survival curve is also called the data set’s half-life. This is the point where half of the observations survive beyond that time \(t\).

Lastly, SAS also provides the visual of the survival curve.

Let’s see this same output for the prisoner recidivism data set. Our time variable here is week while our censoring variable is arrest with the 0 marking that the person was not rearrested which is a censored observation. Note, the calculation table of the survival curve has been suppressed with the notable option due to its length.

proc lifetest data = Survival.Recid notable;
    time week*arrest(0);
run;

R

Let’s look at the survival function for the above visualized data set of six customers. Customers C and F were censored, while customers A, B, D, and E had the events.

We have created those six observations using the first four lines of code below by putting them into a data frame called simple. The Surv function is then used to create our survival object, which R needs to build survival models off of. This survival object specifies the two pieces of our target variable that we are mapping the survival curve for. The first piece is the time = option (or tenure) component called tenure in our data set. The next piece is the event = option flagging censored observations called censored in our data set. The value in the parantheses signifies the observations that are not censored. Note that this is different than SAS which specifies the observations that are censored.

The survfit function will then calculate the KM estimate of the survival curve. We take our survival object recid_simple and put it in a formula with ~ 1 afterwards. We will use this formula in later sections to stratify our analysis. We also use the data = option to specify our data set. The summary and plot functions will then display our results in a table and plot respectively.

customer <- c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E", "F")
tenure <- c( 7, 8, 10, 3, 2, 3)
censored <- c(0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 1)

simple <- data.frame(customer, tenure, censored)

recid_simple <- Surv(time = simple$tenure, event = simple$censored == 0)

simple_km <- survfit(recid_simple ~ 1, data = simple)
summary(simple_km)

Stratified Analysis

Instead of just focusing on one survival curve for the entire sample, we can also split our sample into smaller groups that we think might have different survival curves. We can also statistically test these groups’ survival curves to see if they are the same or not. The primary tests that are used are the Log-Rank test (developed by Mantel and Haenszel) and the Wilcoxon test.

The Log-Rank test combines all the information from the KM estimate at times where events occur. Similar to the Mantel-Haenszel Chi-square test, the Log-rank test then looks for an association in the counts of a cross-tabulation table. The columns of the table are the number of events and number of non-events in each of the rows which are the groups you are subsampling down into. The actual data is compared to the expected values in each cell to develop a Chi-square test statistic:

\[ LogRank = \frac{1}{\hat{\sigma}^2}\times (\sum_{j=1}^r(d_{1,j} - e_{1,j}))^2 \] The Wilcoxon test adds a weight to the above Chi-square test to adjust for differences in sample size along the curve. Since fewer observations exist the further in time you are, the observations at the beginning of the curve are weighted heavier based on this sample size:

\[ Wilcoxon = \frac{1}{\hat{\sigma}^2}\times (\sum_{j=1}^r(d_{1,j} - e_{1,j})n_{j})^2 \] Let’s see how to produce these in each of our softwares!

SAS

Again, SAS uses the PROC LIFETEST prodecure to compute the survival curves. The only addition to this code is the strata statement. Here is the strata statement specifies the variable you want to stratify your data on. We are using the wexp variable to stratify our observations by those who do and do not have previous work experience. As before, the notable option has been used (as well ODS statements) to not display the entire survival tables for both the strata.

ods select html HomTests CensoredSummary SurvivalPlot;
proc lifetest data = Survival.Recid plots=s(cl cb=ep) notable;
    time week*arrest(0);
    strata wexp;
run;

First, SAS provides us a summary of the two strata with how many events and censored observations we have in each. Next, we have the test of equality. The null hypothesis from each of these tests is the same - that the curves are not statistically different than each other. A reasonable significance level for our data is 0.014 and both the log-rank and the Wilcoxon test are significant at this level implying the curves are statistically different. Note, the Likelihood Ratio Test (LRT) is not best used here as it assumes our data follows an exponential distribution which we have not tested. The Log-Rank and Wilcoxon tests do not make an assumption about our data’s distribution. We then see the plot of each of the survival curves along with their respective confidence intervals.

If you had more than two groups, the overall test of significance won’t provide all the detail you need. By using the diff = all option as seen below, you can get pairwise adjusted statistical tests for all combinations of strata. The output is not different since we have two groups.

ods select html SurvDiff;
proc lifetest data = Survival.Recid plots=s(cl cb=ep) notable;
    time week*arrest(0);
    strata wexp / diff=all;
run;

Hazard Function

Outside of survival functions, the other primary function used in survival analysis is the hazard function. There are actually two types of hazard functions - hazard probabilities and hazard rates. Both are denoted the same way across different papers and texts so be careful!

Hazard probabilities are very useful and common in business settings. They define a conditional probability. Given that an observation has not experienced the event before time \(t\), what is the probability that they experience the event before time \(t+1\). It is defined as follows:

\[ h(t) = P(t<T<t+1|T>t) = \frac{d_t}{r_t} \] Notice that this is the ratio contained in the right hand side of the survival function calculation by Kaplan and Meier.

Hazard rates on the other hand have a slightly different use and interpretation because they are limits of conditional probabilities are follows:

\[ h(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \rightarrow 0}\frac{P(t<T<t+\Delta t|T>t)}{\Delta t} \] The hazard rate is the instantaneous event rate for the risk set at time \(t\). Essentially, given survival up until time \(t\), it is the rate of events in the interval \([t, t+\Delta t)\). Although they are bounded below by 0, since these are not probabilities, they are not bounded above by 1. For example, if the hazard rate for contracting a sinus infection is 0.05 with a time measured in months, then you are expected to contract 0.05 sinus infections in the next month (assuming the hazard stays constant). Maybe the inverse is more interpretable. Given that same hazard rate, you could also say that you expect to make it 20 (= 1/0.05) months before contracting your next sinus infection (assuming the hazard stays constant).

Sometimes, we also visualize the cumulative hazard probability, \(\Lambda(t)\), which is just the cumulative hazard rate up until time \(t\).

The survival, hazard, and cumulative hazard functions are all related to each other. These three quantities are all different ways of describing the same distribution. If you know one of them you can compute the others as follows:

  • \(\Lambda(t) = -\log S(t)\)
  • \(S(t) = e^{-\Lambda (t)}\)
  • \(h(t) = -\frac{d}{dt}\log S(t) = \frac{f(t)}{S(t)}\)

Let’s see how to produce these in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS uses PROC LIFETEST to also calculate the hazard function. However, it uses a different technique beyond the KM method to do so. To get the hazard rates and probabilties from SAS, you need to use the actuarial method for calculation. Traditionally, the actuarial method bins time points into intervals to smooth out the estimates of the survival and hazard functions for large data sets. This is still a useful approach for data sets with many time points. For our simple data set (the one with customers A through F), we will calculate this for every time point.

In PROC LIFETEST we use the method = life option in SAS to specify the actuarial method with a width = 1 option to keep the calculation per time point. This function will again give us the calculation of survival for each time point as well as the hazard rates (called hazard) and hazard probabilities (called conditional probabilities of failure). SAS will provide the graph of hazard rates by default. The ods statement takes the life table estimates from SAS and saves them into a new data set called condprob which we use in the PROC SGPLOT procedure to plot the hazard probabilities.

proc lifetest data = Simple method = life width = 1 plots(only)=hazard;
    time tenure*censored(1);
    ods output LifetableEstimates = condprob;
run;

proc sgplot data = condprob;
  styleattrs datacolors=(darkblue darkred) datacontrastcolors=(darkblue darkred);
    series x = lowertime y = condprobfail;
    xaxis label='Tenure';
    title 'Hazard Probability Function';
run;
quit;

Not surprisingly we see two spikes in the hazard plots - either rate or probability. These spikes correspond to the exact same points where the survival function decreases. This is not surprising since the hazard is the rate of event occurring over time while the survival funciton informs us the proportion of events that haven’t experienced the event over time.

We can easily create the cumulative hazard probability curve as well by aggregrating the hazard probabilities as shown in the DATA step below.

ods select html HazardPlot;
proc lifetest data = Simple method = life width = 1 plots=hazard;
    time tenure*censored(1);
    ods output LifetableEstimates = condprob;
run;

data condprob;
    set condprob;
    retain cum_sum;
    cum_sum + condprobfail;
run;

Accelerated Failure Time (AFT) Model

Although the Kaplan-Meier approaches to calculating and comparing survival curves is helpful, it doesn’t fully account for the complexities that an actual model to predict tenure would provide. One popular class of models in survival analysis is the accelerated failure time (AFT) model.

Model Structure

The AFT model is a regression that related the independent variables (sometimes called covariates in survival analysis) to the event time \(T\). The AFT model is a parametric model - it depends on knowledge of the underlying distribution of the data. It takes the following form:

\[ T_i = e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} + \sigma \varepsilon_i} \] This model is obviously non-linear in the relationship between the predictor variables and our target. By taking the natural log of both sides of the equation, we get the following model:

\[ \log T_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} + \sigma \varepsilon_i \] Taking the natural log of tenure ensures that the predictions for tenure will always be positive. We would never want to predict a negative time until an event! The predictor variables are being related to the tenure of an event. Here \(\sigma\) represents the standard deviation of the errors, \(\varepsilon_i\), of our model.

Just as in linear regression, we have assumptions around the errors in our AFT model. The errors in the AFT model can follow many different distributions, but we still assume that they have a constant mean, constant variance, and are independent across observations. Due to censoring in survival analysis data sets, we use maximum likelihood estimation to obtain the estimates of the coefficients (the \(\beta\)’s) in our model instead of ordinary least squares.

Let’s see how to produce these in each of our softwares!

SAS

In SAS, we use PROC LIFEREG to obtain results for an AFT model. The structure of this procedure is similar to the PROC LIFETEST we saw in the previous section. The model statement defines our equation. The target variable is still specified in two pieces - the tenure and whether the event occurred (censoring) - just as in PROC LIFETEST. Here we can also specify predictor variables in the right hand side of the equal sign. There is a class statement to specify and create categorical variables as well. Since all of our categorical variables are binary and have already been reference coded, we do not need to use the class statement here. The dist = option specifies the distribution you assume your errors are following. We will discuss more in later sections on how to test which distribution might be the best one. The ods html select options are used to only display certain pieces of the output.

Interpretation

Let’s talk about interpreting the coefficients from the previous section’s output. If a parameter estimate for a variable is positive then increases in that variable will increase the expected survival time (time until the event). If the parameter estimate is negative then increases in that variables will decrease the expected survival times. If a parameter estimate is zero (or statistically insignificant) then increases in that variable have no impact on the expected survival times.

However, unlike linear regresion, the value of the coefficient isn’t the exact increase in survival time since we look our natural log transformation of the target variable. Instead, we can interpret a transformation of that coefficient. \(100\times (e^{\hat{\beta}} - 1)\) is the % increase in the expected survival time for each one-unit increase in the variable. If the variable is categorical instead, \(100\times (e^{\hat{\beta}} - 1)\) is the % increase in the expected survival time for that category compared to the reference category.

Let’s see how to produce these in each of our softwares!

SAS

In SAS we just add the outest = option to obtain a data set, here called betas, that contains the parameter estimates from our AFT model. From there, a simple DATA STEP will calculate the needed transformation. PROC PRINT then displays the result.

proc lifereg data=Survival.Recid outest=betas noprint;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age mar prio / dist=lnormal;
run;

data betas;
   set betas;
   fin_i = (exp(fin) - 1)*100;
   age_i = (exp(age) - 1)*100;
   mar_i = (exp(mar) - 1)*100;
   prio_i = (exp(prio) - 1)*100;
   keep fin_i age_i mar_i prio_i;
run;

proc print data=betas;
run;
Obs fin_i age_i mar_i prio_i
1 39.3574 3.38643 75.2237 -7.16307

Let’s interpret both a categorical and continuous variable. First, the categorical variable of financial aid. Here we can see that people who were given financial aid have an estimated 39.36% increase in expected time until rearrest, holding all else constant in the model. Next, let’s look at the continuous variable for number of previous convictions. Every additional previous conviction decreases the expected time until rearrest by 7.16%, holding all else constant in the model. These increases are percentage increases at every point in time. Therefore, the actual change in tenure time is different depending on predicted failure time. The survival curves essentially diverge, but are not parallel.

Model Assumptions

Recall from earlier that AFT models are parametric models as we assume failure time has a particular structure and distribution. The Kaplan-Meier estimate makes no assumption on failure time - a nonparametric approach. Parametric methods allow for more detailed/precise estimation than nonparametric methods if the distribution is specified correctly.

Remember the structure we have for the AFT model:

\[ \log T_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} + \sigma \varepsilon_i \] The scale term (\(\sigma\)) describes the spread of the distribution of the errors. Another common form is the inverse of the scale - called the rate: \(\lambda = 1/\sigma\). If \(\sigma\) is small, then events are not spread out. In other words, events are happening close together and the rate of events (\(\lambda\)) is large.

Common Distributions

We will focus on the distribution of failure time \(T\) as compared to the error itself since this is the typical input for software to define the distribution of the model. The hardest part is trying to evaluate which distribution is the best distribution. Two common approaches are:

  1. Visualization
  2. Statistical Tests

You should never really think about these evaluations as which distribution is the “correct” distribution. The following contains commonly used distributions for survival data, but there is no guarantee that your data will adequately match just one of the distributions here, or even any of them at all.

First, let’s examine the exponential distribution. This is the simplest of all of the distributions we will cover because it has a constant hazard that doesn’t depend on time.

  • Survival Function: \(S(t) = e^{-\lambda t}\)
  • Hazard Function: \(h(t) = \lambda\)

The exponential distribution works great when failures are completely random. For example, a light bulb breaking, electronic failures, etc.

The next distribution is the Weibull distribution. This is the most commonly used distribution in survival analysis. This distribution has two parameters - scale and shape and is defined as follows:

  • Survival Function: \(S(t) = e^{-(\lambda t)^\gamma}\)
  • Hazard Function: \(h(t) = \lambda \gamma (\lambda t)^{\gamma - 1}\)

The shape parameter, \(\gamma\), determines whether the hazard increases or decreases with time. If \(\gamma > 1\) then the hazard increases with time. For example, aging parts on a var wear out over time. If \(\gamma < 1\) then the hazard decreases with time. For example, post-surgery complications happen fewer and fewer the further from the surgery date. Notice that the hazard for the Weibull distribution is constant when \(\gamma = 1\) - the exponential distribution! The exponential distribution is a special case of the Weibull distribution. All of our softwares test this automatically when running AFT models. R uses a hypothesis test to see if the natural log of the scale term equals 0. Scale here is defined as \(1/\gamma\) so the natural log of this would be 0 if \(\gamma = 1\). SAS uses the Lagrange multuiplier test for scale to directly test if \(\gamma = 1\) instead. Be careful when looking at output from either SAS or R with regards to the naming conventions of the parameters. The naming convention in a distributional sense for the Weibull is rate (\(\lambda\)) and shape (\(\gamma\)). However, in an AFT model, the parameterizations change around. Refer to the table below for details:

Weibull Parameterizations

Another common distribution is the log-normal distribution. If \(T\) has a log-normal distribution, then the errors, \(\varepsilon\), follow a normal distribution. If there is no censoring, an AFT model with a log-normal tenure distribution is the same as a linear regression with \(y = \log(T)\).

All of the above distributions are part of a family of distributions called the Gamma family of distributions. The generalized gamma distribution has all of the above distributions as special cases.

The log-logistic distribution is another common distribution. This distribution allows the hazard to increase and then decrease if its shape parameter \(\gamma > 1\). The log-logistic AFT model is just an ordinal logistic regression model.

The generalized F distribution actually contains all of the gamma family of distributions as well as the log-logistic distribution as special cases as well. The following chart represents how all these distributions are nested within each other in some form.

Nested Distributions

The relationships between all these distributions underly the visualization and statistical tests for comparing the distributions to find the best one.

Visual Comparisons

The first approach to finding the best distribution out of the collection is through visualizations.We take the known equations for each of the distributions and compare our data to the theoretical distribution we are fitting.

Let’s take a look at how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS uses probability plots to help visualize the distributions. To change what distribution you are fitting to the AFT model you just change the name in the dist = option. SAS will provide a probability plot to compare your data to the theoretical distribution with the probplot statement. If our data fits the distribution well, we should see it follow a relatively straight diagonal line. The theoretical diagonal line as well as its confidence interval is plotted for us to compare with. The alpha = option helps define the confidence interval. Let’s compare our prisoner recidivism data set AFT model to the exponential distribution. Note that all of the variables in the model. Since we are unsure of the distribution, we cannot trust the statistical tests on the variables. It is best to perform this piece with all the variables present.

However, it also appears as if the data might follow a log-logistic distribution as well. This is where things become difficult with the visualizations. The log-logistic is NOT a special case of the Weibull so those cannot be directly compared. In fact, the log-logistic isn’t even a special case of the gamma distribution. Statistical tests might be of some more help.

Goodness-of-Fit Tests

Luckily, most of the distributions we went over earlier are nested versions of each other in some way. That means we can use statistical tests that compare nested models to compare these models and the underlying distributions. We will use the likelihood ratio test since these models are all estimated with MLE. The likelihood ratio test assumes two models (one being nested within the other) are the same. If the two models are statistically different, then the larger (more complex) of the two is finding more information. If they are the same statistically, then the complexity of the larger model provides no additional benefit and we go with the simpler model. The test statistic is the following:

\[ LRT = -2(\log(L_{nested}) - \log(L_{full}))) \] Again, just as with the plotting, we use the full model since we cannot rely on the statistical tests of the model with an incorrect distribution. The following table provides the log-likelihood value obtained from the softwares for each model.

Likelihood Values from AFT Models
Log-Likelihood Value Implied Distribution Software
-686.37 Exponential SAS/R
-679.92 Weibull SAS/R
-683.23 Log-Normal SAS/R
-679.92 Generalized Gamma SAS/R
-679.94 Log-Logistic SAS/R
-678.72 Generalized F R

Let’s use each of our softwares to compare these models through the LRT!

SAS

With SAS we can easily perform the LRT through the DATA step. Here we can just run the calculation directly. After inputting the log-likelihood values from the unlogged target variable piece of the fit statistics from SAS we can then directly calculate the LRT for any nested comparison. Here we are comparing the exponential to the generalized gamma, the Weibull to the generalized gamma, and the log-normal to the generalized gamma. The degrees of freedom on these tests are just the difference in the number of parameters between the distributions since all the mdoels have the same number of variables. For example, The exponential has only one parameter to estimate, but the generalized gamma has three. Therefore, the degrees of freedom would be 2. Early in the code above, we saw that the Weibull is the statistical choice if choosing between it and the exponential.

data GOF;
    Exp = -686.37;
  Weib = -679.92;
  LNorm = -683.23;
  GGam = -679.92;

    LRT1 = -2*(Exp - GGam);
    LRT2 = -2*(Weib - GGam);
    LRT3 = -2*(LNorm - GGam);

    P_Value1 = 1 - probchi(LRT1,2);
    P_Value2 = 1 - probchi(LRT2,1);
    P_Value3 = 1 - probchi(LRT3,1);
run;

proc print data=GOF;
    var LRT1-LRT3 P_Value1-P_Value3;
run;
Obs LRT1 LRT2 LRT3 P_Value1 P_Value2 P_Value3
1 12.9 0 6.62 .001580522 1 0.010084

After printing our results with PROC PRINT, we can see the comparisons. Remember, the null hypothesis is that the two models are equal. If this is the case we will go with the simpler model. However, if this isn’t the case, we need to go with the more complicated model since it performs better. Based on these results, the gamma distribution outperforms both the log-normal and the exponential. However, it doesn’t outperform the Weibull distribution. From these three tests, it appears that the Weibull distribution is the best choice. This does NOT mean that our data fits the Weibull distribution necessarily. It is just saying that the Weibull is the best distribution among the choices we have tested.

R

With R we can easily perform the LRT. Here we can just run the calculation directly. We can extract the log-likelihood value directly from our model objects and store them as separate objects. We can then directly calculate the LRT for any nested comparison. Here we are comparing the exponential to the generalized gamma, the Weibull to the generalized gamma, the log-normal to the generalized gamma, the generalized gamma to the generalized F, and the log-logistic to the generalized F. The degrees of freedom on these tests are just the difference in the number of parameters between the distributions since all the mdoels have the same number of variables. For example, The exponential has only one parameter to estimate, but the generalized gamma has three. Therefore, the degrees of freedom would be 2. Early in the code above, we saw that the Weibull is the statistical choice if choosing between it and the exponential.

like.e <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "exp")$loglik
like.w <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "weibull")$loglik
like.ln <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "lnorm")$loglik
like.g <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "gamma")$loglik
like.ll <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "llogis")$loglik
like.f <- flexsurvreg(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar + paro + prio, data = recid, dist = "genf")$loglik

pval.e.g <- 1 - pchisq((-2*(like.e-like.g)), 2)
pval.w.g <- 1 - pchisq((-2*(like.w-like.g)), 1)
pval.ln.g <- 1 - pchisq((-2*(like.ln-like.g)), 1)
pval.g.f <- 1 - pchisq((-2*(like.g-like.f)), 1)
pval.ll.f <- 1 - pchisq((-2*(like.ll-like.f)), 1)

Tests <- c('Exp vs. Gam', 'Wei vs. Gam', 'LogN vs. Gam', 'Gam vs. F', 'LogL vs. F')
P_values <- c(pval.e.g, pval.w.g, pval.ln.g, pval.g.f, pval.ll.f)
cbind(Tests, P_values)
     Tests          P_values             
[1,] "Exp vs. Gam"  "0.00172559564523367"
[2,] "Wei vs. Gam"  "1"                  
[3,] "LogN vs. Gam" "0.0110221983305441" 
[4,] "Gam vs. F"    "0.108860911475402"  
[5,] "LogL vs. F"   "0.118276422245853"

After combining our results with a couple extra lines of code, we can see the comparisons. Remember, the null hypothesis is that the two models are equal. If this is the case we will go with the simpler model. However, if this isn’t the case, we need to go with the more complicated model since it performs better. Based on these results, the gamma distribution outperforms both the log-normal and the exponential. However, it doesn’t outperform the Weibull distribution. We can see that the F distribution does not outperform either of the gamma or log-logistic. From these tests, it appears that the Weibull distribution or the log-logistic distribution are both valid choices. Which to choose? From the visual inspections we leaned towards the Weibull so that is what we will go with. This does NOT mean that our data fits the Weibull distribution necessarily. It is just saying that the Weibull is the best distribution among the choices we have tested.

Predicting Survival & Event Times

AFT models assume a distribution for \(T\), meaning that we expect event times to behave in a certain way. IF we assume the correct distribution, we can predict quantiles, survival probabilities, event times, survival curves, and changes in the expected event time as predictor variables change value. Some example predictions are:

  • Median survival time: \(\hat{S}_i(t) = 0.5\)
  • Time which \(q\)% of people with the same predictor values have the event: \(\hat{S}_i(t) = 1-q\)
  • The 20 week survival probability: \(\hat{S}_i(20)\)

Careful though! The predictions of \(\hat{S}_i(t)\) completely depend on the distribution used so predictions will NOT be the same across different distributions. This is why it is important to pick the best distribution we can.

Let’s see how to get these predictions in our different softwares!

SAS

Let’s first look at the quantiles from our survival probability predictions. For each observation in our data set we can estimate any quantile on their observation specific survival curve. We can easily do this in SAS using the output statement in PROC LIFEREG. We build our model as previously described using the Weibull distribution (based on our distribution results above). In the output statement we use the out = option to define the data set where these will be stored, the p = option to define the name of our predictions column in the data set, the std_err = option to define the name of the standard errors column, and the quantile = option to define the quantiles we want to estimate for each observation. Here we ask for the quartiles. We then only print out the first 9 observations (quartiles for the first 3 observations) in our data set.

proc lifereg data=Survival.Recid noprint;
    model Week*arrest(0) = fin age prio / dist=weibull;
    output out=recid_q p=quan quantile=(0.25, 0.50, 0.75) std_err=se;
run;

proc print data=recid_q (obs = 9);
    var week _PROB_ quan se;
run;

Next, we can predict an expected change in event time when we change the value of a predictor variable. For this example, we want to predict the new survival time for individuals who were not given financial aid if they had been given financial aid. To do this, we first need to fit the model and output some results. PROC LIFEREG still has our AFT model built on the Weibull distribution. However, now we ask for different output from the output statement. We use the xbeta = option to provide the predicted natural log of survival time. We name it lp because it is sometimes referred to as the linear portion of the model. We also want the survival probability at the event time in the data set. SAS provides the failure probability (the opposite of survival) with the cdf = option. We also extract the parameter estimates of our model using the outest = option in the PROC LIFEREG statement.

The next piece of code uses a DATA step to create MACRO variables for our shape parameter (defined as the inverse of the scale parameter from the outest = data set) and the financial aid variable’s coefficient. The next DATA step subsets our data to just the individuals who were rearrested and who did not receive financial aid (deleting observations who did not meet those requirements). We then calculate the survival probability as the opposite of the failure probability. Next, we calculate the new prediction of the log of survival time by taking the original lp variable and adding the effect of the coefficient for the financial aid. Remember, financial aid is just a binary variable, so by adding the coefficient, we are just adding the effect if that observation had been given financial aid. We need to then pinpoint this new prediction on the Weibull distribution. We use the squantile function for the Weibull distribution, along with the survival probability of that observation, the shape parameter from our outest = data set, and this new prediction of the survival time (remember to take the exp function to negate the natural log). Effectively, we are assuming that the individual would be rearrested at the point when their survival probability reached the point they were rearrested in our data set. Our goal here is to extend that survival curve out as much as possible using the financial aid variable.

proc lifereg data=Survival.Recid outest=Beta noprint;
    model Week*arrest(0) = fin age prio / dist=weibull;
    output out=recid_e xbeta=lp cdf=cdistfunc;
run;

data _null_;
    set Beta;
    call symput('shape', 1/_SCALE_);
    call symput('beta_fin', fin);
run;

data recid_e;
    set recid_e;
    if arrest = 0 then delete;
    if fin = 1 then delete;
    survprob = 1 - cdistfunc;
    
    lp_new = lp + &beta_fin;
    
    newtime = squantile('weibull', survprob, &shape, exp(lp_new));
    diff = newtime - week;
run;

proc print data=recid_e (obs = 3);
    var survprob lp lp_new week newtime diff;
run;

Here we are looking at the first three observations from our subsetting data set of just individuals who were rearrested and did not originally have financial aid. We can see that the first individual would have had a predicted increase in survival time until rearrest of 5.67 weeks. This approach can be used to measure the impacts of a variety of variables to see which ones might be best used.

Using a new function, the psurvreg function, in conjunction with the predict function, we can obtain estimated survival probabilities at any time point. The psurvreg function has four main inputs. The qsurvreg function has four main inputs. The first input is the survival probability of interest. This comes from the above code where we store the survival probability of each observation at the point of the event (or when they were censored). The next three options are the mean = option to specify the predicted natural log of event time from the predict function with type = "lp", the scale = option to specify the predicted scale of the distribution from the model object, and the dist = option to specify the distribution from the AFT model that was assumed. Cox Regression

The Accelerated Failure Time model has a big disadvantage - needing to estimate the distribution of our data. With an incorrect distribution, we will get incorrect results. The other big class of models in survival analysis is the Cox regression. These models do not have the distribution assumption of the AFT model. However, that doesn’t mean they don’t have their own disadvantages as well. Let’s learn more about them!

Proportional Hazards

Instead of modeling event time, the Cox regression model focuses on modeling hazards. The most popular hazard model is the proportional odds model:

\[ \log h(t) = \log h_0(t) + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} \] In other words, we are predicting the hazard function defined in this way:

\[ h(t) = h_0(t)e^{\beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k}} \] In the above equations, \(h_0(t)\) is the baseline hazard function which is dependent on the distribution of the hazard function. The variables (and their coefficients) shift the predicted hazard from this baseline hazard.

The reason the proportional hazard model is so popular is that we actually look at the ratio between two individuals (i and j) instead of predicting the hazard on any one:

\[ \frac{h_i(t)}{h_j(t)} = e^{\beta_1 (x_{i,1} - x_{j,1}) + \cdots + \beta_k (x_{i,k} - x_{j,k})} \] The novelty of this approach is that it removes the distribution piece - the baseline hazard. This means our estimation is no longer time dependent as there is a constant proportion on hazards. The AFT model depended on the distribution of time, where the proportional hazards model can be estimated without this dependence. This estimation is not trivial and is discussed in a later section.

This leads to the main disadvantage though of the proportional hazard model. The results do not say how long an individual will last, only the relative length of tenure between two groups. Essentially, our conclusions would look something like this: “On average, a customer who signed up via direct mail stays twice as long compared to a customer who signed up via telemarketing.” We no longer predict the time until an event, just the relative difference between two groups for that event. This works when we assume that factors measured at an initial time point have an uniform proportional effect (hence the name of the model) on hazards between individuals/groups.

Let’s see how to build one of these in each of our softwares!

SAS

In SAS we use PROC PHREG to obtain estimates from a proportional hazards model. The model statement has the same structure as we previously saw for the AFT model. The ties = efron deals with how the estimation (covered later) handles observations with the same failure time. The profile likelihood estimation approach is the best approach for confidence intervals for the hazard ratio (the risklimits = pl option).

ods select html FitStatistics ConvergenceStatus ParameterEstimates;

    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties=efron risklimits=pl;

First, we can see that SAS reports some common fit statistics for our model - the -2 log likelihood value, AIC, and BIC. These are only comparison metrics. There is no true metric that defines if these are good or bad because it is relative to the data set that you have. Once we build other models, we can then compare. We also noticed that the algorithm to estimate the model converged. This is very important to have otherwise our results are not reliable.

Next, we have the analysis of the variables themselves. The parameter estimates table provides us the actual estimates for the AFT model equation. Along with the variable parameter estimates, we also have an estimate for the intercept for the model (at the top of the table).

A key piece of the parameter estimates table is the hazard ratio column. The hazard ratio is just the exponentiated value of the parameter estimate, \(e^{\beta}\). This helps interpret the parameter estimates and the respective relationship between predictor variables and the target. If a parameter estimate is positive, then increases in that variable increase the expected hazard. This would also lead to a hazard ratio above 1 and implies an increase in the rate/risk of failure. If a parameter estimate is negative, then increases in that variable decrease the expected hazard. This leads to a hazard ratio below 1 and implies a decrease in the rate/risk of failure.

Just like with the AFT model, we can interpret the following transformation as well. \(100\times (e^{\hat{\beta}} - 1)\) is the % increase in the expected hazard (rate of failure) for each one-unit increase in the variable. If the variable is categorical instead, \(100\times (e^{\hat{\beta}} - 1)\) is the % increase in the expected hazard for that category compared to the reference category.

In the code below, we extract the coefficients from our model using the outest = option. We then perform this transformation in the DATA step. PROC PRINT is then used to print out the calculations.

proc phreg data=Survival.Recid outest=betas noprint;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age prio / ties=efron risklimits=pl;
run;

data betas;
   set betas;
   fin_i = (exp(fin) - 1)*100;
   age_i = (exp(age) - 1)*100;
   prio_i = (exp(prio) - 1)*100;
   keep fin_i age_i prio_i;
run;

proc print data=betas;
run;

Next, let’s look at the continuous variable for number of previous convictions. Every additional previous conviction increases the expected hazard of rearrest by 10.2%, holding all else constant in the model.

Estimation

Quickly, let’s discuss the estimation of the Cox regression model. In both accelerated failure time and proportional hazards models, estimation depends on some distributional assumption around either the failure time or the baseline hazard. However, in proportional hazard models, Cox noticed that the likelihood can be split into two pieces:

  1. A piece that depends on both the baseline hazard and the parameters (coefficients) - treated as non-parametric
  2. A piece that depends only on the parameters (coefficients) - treated as parametric

This is why the model is called semiparametric. Basically, using the semiparametric approach we disregard the first piece of the likelihood function and maximize the second piece - called partial maximum likelihood estimate. This partial maximum likelihood estimation is done on the ranks of the failure times. This is why we need to specify how to handle observations with tied ranks (equal failure times). The beauty of this approach is that it removes the baseline hazard and its distributional assumption from the estimation. The downside of this approach is that some of the information will be lost in estimating the coefficients. This information loss is rather small though and our estimates are still unbiased and can be tested statistically.

This lack of the baseline hazard distribution in the calculation of the estimates leads to the biggest disadvantage of the Cox regression model. It cannot estimate any absolute predictions of time or risk. All inference and predictions are relative and comparison in nature.

Diagnostics

Although we have no distributional assumptions on the tenure or hazard itself in the Cox regression model, we still have assumptions on the model itself that we need to check.

  1. Linearity
  2. Proportional Hazards

Both of these assumptions depend on calculations of different types of residuals in survival analysis.

Residuals

There are four kinds of rseiduals for survival models, all with various uses:

  • Martingale (check linearity, check proportional hazards, detect outliers)
  • Schoenfeld (check proportional hazards)
  • Deviance (check linearity, detect outliers)
  • Score (detect influential observations)

We will focus on the first two.

Martingale residuals are the difference between the observed number of events and the expected number of events at a specific point in time. A positive residual exists when an observation had the event sooner than expected. A negative residual exists when the observation had the event later than expected. These are not symmetrical around zero however since hazard is bounded by 0.

Schoenfeld residuals are calculated for each variable for each observation. They are the difference between the actual value of the variable and the expected value for an observation who had the event occur at that time.

Let’s see how each of these help us evaluate the assumptions of linearity and proportional hazards.

Linearity

Essentially, the linearity of the model tests whether we need higher order (polynomial) terms on the variables that we have. This is only tested on continuous variables as it would not make sense to have higher order terms on categorical variables. Each software takes different approaches to evaluating the linearity of the model. R uses martingale residual plots for checking linearity of predictors by plotting the residuals vs the predictor. This is a similar approach to looking for residual patterns in linear regression to reveal a lack of linearity. SAS on the other hand uses cumulative martingale residual plots compared to the predictor. Comparing these cumulative residuals across time can also be used for determining linearity.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS can test linearity inside of PROC PHREG. We build our proportional hazards model as we have previous seen using the model statement. Now we add the assess statement to evaluate our two continuous variables - age and prio. We use the var = (age prio) option to define the variables we want to test the linearity on. The resample option specifies that we want ot use simulation to perform this test.

ods html select FunctionalFormSupTest CumulativeResiduals;
proc phreg data = Survival.Recid;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age prio / ties=efron;
    assess var=(age prio) / resample;
run;

Let’s talk about the above plots. SAS randomly simulates possible paths of residuals that are produced from a linear model. Ideally, our residuals should be randomly, horizontally scattered around zero with no pattern. Any pattern would imply a lack of linearity. SAS computes the probability we observed our sample among the 1000 simulated samples it calculated. If our model’s residuals are rare enough, we will no longer be able to assume our variable is linearly related to our model. We can see that the p-value for age is 0.0330 and for prio is 0.5860. These are both above our stated significance level of 0.015 which means that we can not reject our assumption of linearity.

R

R can test linearity visually with the visreg function. We input our model object first. The next input is a character string for the variables of interest in our model - age and prio. Lastly we have some other options for visual appeal.

visreg(recid.ph, "age", xlab = "age", ylab = "partial residuals", gg = TRUE,

Let’s talk about the above plots. R fits a spline through the residuals to try and pick up the underlying pattern in the residuals. It then puts a line that would represent the linear relationship of the variables in our model. If linearity holds we should see the confidence interval completely cover the straight line. We can see some slight departures from this pattern, but overall it looks like it captures the line in both plots.

Test for Proportional Hazards

The other major assumption in the proportional hazards model is in the name - proportional hazards. Remember, proportional hazards implies our estimation is no longer time dependent as there is a constant proportion on hazards. This is a rather strong assumption for all of our variables.

Each software has slightly different approaches that are available to test this assumption. Let’s see how each of our softwares performs this!

SAS

There are a couple of different ways to test for proportional hazards in SAS. The first way uses martingale residuals. SAS creates a random walk time series for your residuals across tenure since there should be no pattern to the residuals if they meet the proportional hazards assumption. If your model produces residuals with more than expected pattern, then you have a problem with the assumption.

Again, we can test this assumption using options in PROC PHREG. Just like with our linearity assumption, we will use the assess statement. Here, we will also specify the ph option so that the proportional hazard assumption is retested. The resample option specifies that we want ot use simulation to perform this test.

Notice how we are testing this on all the variables in the original data. This is due to the fact that if the proportional hazard assumption isn’t met, we can not trust the p-values from the hypothesis tests. Ideally, we test this assumption as one of the first steps in building a Cox regression model.

ods html select ProportionalHazardsSupTest;
proc phreg data=Survival.Recid;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties=efron;
    assess ph / resample;
run;

In later sections, we will use age to build some non-proportional hazard models.

SAS also uses Schoenfeld residuals to investigate the relationship of variables across time since these residuals are calculated on a variable by variable basis. We either plot these residuals against functions of time or test the correlation between these residuals and functions of time with the later being the most popular. Common examples of time functions are the linear function \(t\) and the natural log of time \(\log(t)\). If this correlation is statistically different than zero, we say the assumption of proportional hazards is not met. We can perform all three of these comparisons using the zph option. Inside the zph option are sub-options. The global sub-option calculates the global version of the test. The transform = option tells SAS which transformation you would like to test - identity for linear time, and log for natural log of time.

ods html select zphTest;
proc phreg data = Survival.Recid zph(global transform=identity);
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties = efron;
run;

ods html select zphTest;
proc phreg data = Survival.Recid zph(global transform=log);
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties = efron;

Automatic Selection Techniques

With the distributional assumptions out of the way thanks to the above partial maximum likelihood approach, we can jump right into variable selection. Stepwise selection techniques involve the three common methods:

  1. Forward Selection
  2. Backward Selection
  3. Stepwise Selection

These techniques add or remove (depending the technique) one variable at a time from your regression model to try and “improve” the model. There are a variety of different selection criteria to use to add or remove variables from a model. The softwares we explore use different approaches so let’s examine each one!

SAS

PROC PHREG uses significance levels and p-values for adding or removing variables from the stepwise selection techniques. Although p-values are falling out of popularity, it is primarily because people often use the 0.05 significance level without any regards to sample size. Although 0.05 is a good significance level for a sample size around 50, this level should be adjusted based on sample size. The mathematical details are not covered here, but it can be shown that the BIC criterion for adding or removing variables with stepwise selection (which is becoming very popular) is the same thing as using p-values in likelihood ratio tests. However, the significance level changes depending on sample size due to the BIC equation, which is exactly what is recommended for any selection techniques using p-values.

Stepwise Selection

Here we will work through stepwise selection. In stepwise selection, the initial model is empty (contains no variables, only the intercept). Each variable is then tried to see if it is significant based on p-value and a specified significance level. The most significant variable (if any) is then added to the model. Next, all variables in the model (here only one) are tested to see if they are still significant. If not, they are dropped. If so, then the remaining variables are again tested and the next most significant variable is added to the model. This process repeats until either no more significant variables are available to add or the same variable keeps being added and then removed from the model.

PROC PHREG uses the selection = stepwise option to perform this technique. Notice also the slentry = and slstay = options where we specify the significance to both enter and stay in the model respectively. Here we chose 0.015 based on our sample size.

ods html select ModelBuildingSummary ParameterEstimates;
proc phreg data=Survival.Recid;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties=efron selection=stepwise
                                                           slentry=0.015 slstay=0.015;
run;

Backward Selection

Here we will work through backward selection. In backward selection, the initial model is full (contains all variables, including the intercept). Each variable is then tried to see if it is significant based on p-value and a specified significance level. The least significant variable (if any) is then dropped from the model. Then the remaining variables are again tested and the next least significant variable is dropped from the model. This process repeats until no more insignificant variables are available to drop.

PROC PHREG uses the selection = backward option to perform this technique. Notice also the slstay = option where we specify the significance to stay in the model. Here we chose 0.015 based on our sample size.

R’s step function uses either AIC or BIC adding or removing variables from the stepwise selection techniques. Although p-values are falling out of popularity, it is primarily because people often use the 0.05 significance level without any regards to sample size. The mathematical details are not covered here, but it can be shown that the BIC criterion for adding or removing variables with stepwise selection (which is becoming very popular) is the same thing as using p-values in likelihood ratio tests. Stepwise Selection

Here we will work through stepwise selection. In stepwise selection, the initial model is empty (contains no variables, only the intercept). Each variable is then tried to see if it is significant based on p-value and a specified significance level. The most significant variable (if any) is then added to the model. Next, all variables in the model (here only one) are tested to see if they are still significant. If not, they are dropped. If so, then the remaining variables are again tested and the next most significant variable is added to the model. This process repeats until either no more significant variables are available to add or the same variable keeps being added and then removed from the model.

In R we must specify two models - the empty and full models - to step between. Notice the full model contains all the variables, while the empty model contains only the intercept (signified by ~ 1 in the formula). We then use the step function where we start at the empty model. The scope option tells R the lower (lower =) and upper (upper =) model to step between. The direction = "both" option tells R to use stepwise selection.

full.model <- coxph(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ fin + age + race + wexp + mar +paro + prio, 
                    data = recid)

empty.model <- coxph(Surv(week, arrest == 1) ~ 1, data = recid)

step.model <- step(empty.model, 
                   scope = list(lower=formula(empty.model), 
                                upper=formula(full.model)), 
                   direction = "both", trace = 0)

Predictions

There are some forms of predictions that we can get for the Cox regression model, even if they aren’t as well defined as the AFT mdoel. Once we have obtained parameter estimates from the partial likelihood estimation, we can plug in into the full likelihood and non-parametrically estimate the remaining piece of the likelihood. It is essentially combining the concepts of partial MLE and Kaplan-Meier. This helps us estimate the survival curves for predefined combinations of the predictor variables.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

In SAS we can “score” these new observations right in our PROC PHREG procedure. First, let’s create a couple of observations of interest using the DATA step. Here we define two new observations with slightly different inputs. In PROC PHREG we use the baseline statement along with the covariates = option to define the data set that needs to be scored. The out = option defines the name of the data set we will save our results to.

data ref;
    input fin age race wexp mar paro prio;
datalines;
1 30 0 1 0 0 0
0 30 0 0 0 0 4
;
run;

ods html select SurvivalPlot;
proc phreg data=Survival.Recid plots(overlay)=survival;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio / ties = efron risklimits=pl;
    baseline covariates=ref out=refs;

From the output above we can see the two survival curves for the observations we defined in our data set. With these survival curves, we can estimate quantile survival times, such as the median.

Model Assessment

It is always of interest to know how “well” our model did. Due to censoring as well as Cox regression making relative predictions, model evaluation is not easy/intuitive to evaluate.

Concordance is a popular method to assess model performance. The classical definition for concordance is that for all possible event and non-event pairs, we want to assign the higher predicted value to the subject that had the event. There is a different spin on this definition for survival analysis - we assign a higher “risk” to the subject that had the event first. Essentially, we want to know how well the model ranks who will have the event sooner. What is “risk” in this context? It is the linear piece to our model: \(\hat{\beta}_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_k x_{i,k}\). Let’s compare two individuals:

  1. Person 1 - event at time 3, and \(\hat{\beta}_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_k x_{i,k} = 1.5\)
  2. Person 2 - event (or censored) at time 7, and \(\hat{\beta}_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_k x_{i,k} = 0.3\)

The above pair is concordant because the person with the higher “risk” had the event first. If both people have the same event time or censoring time, then the pair is incomparable and we do not count it. Censoring can lead to some hard comparisons though. Let’s look at the following two individuals:

  1. Person 1 - censored at time 3, and \(\hat{\beta}_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_k x_{i,k} = 1.5\)
  2. Person 2 - event (or censored) at time 7, and \(\hat{\beta}_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \hat{\beta}_k x_{i,k} = 0.3\)

This pair is unknown - called indeterminate since there is no way to know which person had the event first. If both people have the same predicted “risk” then the pair is considered a tie and counted as 0.5.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS still uses PROC PHREG to get the main model output. All we have to do is add the concordance option to get the concordance calculations.

Non-Proportional Hazards Models

What if the assumption for proportional hazards doesn’t hold? What if our variables are changing across time? Both of these situations lead to non-proportional hazards models. Two common reasons you don’t have proportional hazards are the following:

  1. Time-Dependent Coefficients
  2. Time-Dependent Variables

Time Dependent Coefficients

Models up until this point have assumed that predictors have a constant effect, \(\beta\), on the target variable. In proportional hazards models, we assume effects are constant over time, so that the hazard reatio is independent of time. What if this didn’t hold true and the effect of a predictor variable could change across time? For example, what if age didn’t have a constant effect across time? These effects, now \(\beta(t)\), are called time-varying coefficients or time-dependent coefficients. Now at least one of the variable’s coefficients in the model becomes the following:

\[ \log h(t) = \log h_0 (t) + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_j (t) x_{i,j} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} \]

These time-varying coefficients are functions of time. For example, it could be a linear function of time:

\[ \beta_j (t) = \beta_j + b\times t \]

If \(b = 0\), then the effect doesn’t depend on time (proportional hazards assumption satisfied). If \(b \ne 0\), then the effect does depend on time (proportional hazards assumption failed). As mentioned in the Diagnostics section of the notes, Schoenfeld residuals are best used for investigating relationships with time for predictor variables. Earlier we saw that the age variable seemed to break the proportional hazards assumption and that it was correlated the highest with the \(\log (t)\) transformation. That means that our age variable has a coefficient like the following:

\[ \beta_{age} (t) = \beta_{age} + b\times \log(week) \]

CAREFUL! This is NOT like creating a standard interaction with time for your predictor variable. The interaction must be constructed in a way that updates at each time point. Luckily, our softwares can easily do this for us.

Let’s see how our softwares can account for this!

SAS

PROC PHREG can build these time-varying coefficients for you if you specify the time-varying nature of them. Notice in the model statement below we have two new variables agelogweek and wexpweek. These two variables have actually been created in the statements below the model statement. Here we create agelogweek = age*log(week). This tells SAS that we want the coefficient on the age variable to be time-varying with \(\log(t)\) to be the function of time. The wexp variable is given the identity function as well.

ods html select ParameterEstimates;
proc phreg data=Survival.Recid;
    model week*arrest(0) = fin age race wexp mar paro prio agelogweek wexpweek / ties=efron;
    agelogweek = age*log(week);
    wexpweek = wexp*week;
run;

Time Dependent Variables

Similar to time-dependent coefficients, time-dependent variables have the actual value of the predictor variable (rather than its effect) change over time. For example, age at entry and race would be independent variable examples since they don’t change. However, variables like employment status and blood pressure might change over a survival analysis study. Now at least one of the variables in the model becomes the following:

\[ \log h(t) = \log h_0 (t) + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_j x_{i,j}(t) + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} \]

In our prisoner recidivism data, we have variables measuring the full time employment status during each of the 52 weeks of the study. Ideally, time-dependent variables are measured at the same regular interval as the response variable. If this is not the case, we use common-sense guessing to adjust.

The most important thing to remember with time-dependent variables is that future data can not be used to predict the past - called immortal time bias. Although it would seem obvious, this mistake happens quite frequently.

For time-dependent variables, it is necessary to split the time column of your data set into separate start and stop columns. This is known as the counting process structure/layout to your data. In a counting process structure, an observation is split when one of their time-dependent variables change. Imagine an observation has an event at time \(t = 9\), but their value of \(x\) changes changes after \(t = 5\). This observation is split into two observations as show below:

Counting Process Example

In the first observation, our observation starts at time 0 and stops at time 5 with the event being censored since it has yet to occur. The value of our time dependent variable \(x\) is 3. In the second observation, our observation starts at time 5 and stops at time 9 where the event occurs. Notice however that the time dependent variable \(x\) has a value of 7. This structure must be done for each original observation across each of the variables changing over time.

The most difficult part of modeling time-dependent variables is the formatting of the data correctly. This is rather tedious but typically straight-forward. R requires the data be structured in this way, while SAS will do this for you. Every other step of modeling is the same.

Let’s examine how to incorporate time-dependent variables in each of our softwares!

SAS

As mentioned above, SAS will implement the time-dependent variables without needing the counting process structure as long as you have separate columns of data for each time varying predictor variable at each time point. In our prisoner recidivism data set we have variables emp1 through emp52 as binary flags for full time employment during that week. Using the array statement, we can define the emp(*) array using the emp1 through emp52 variables. It is easiest to do this if your variables are only different in numerical value at the end of their name. We then create an employed variable which flags if the individual is employed for each week. This is also added to our model statement. Again, this is NOT a variable flagging if as individual was employed at their week of arrest. It is a variable that notes the individual’s employment at each week and takes that into account in the estimation of the variable.

ods html select ParameterEstimates;
proc phreg data=Survival.Recid;

    array emp(*) emp1-emp52;

Competing Risks

All of the models used so far have been studying the time until one event occurs. However, all of these models can be used extended to studying multiple events or multiple types of events. The idea of competing risks is that each observation can experience only one of several mutually exclusive possible events. If an observation experiences another type of event, it is censored for the event we are studying.

In competing risks we still have a notion of independence. Remember from above, we assume the event time \(T_i\) and censor time \(C_i\) are independent - observations censored at time \(t\) were randomly selected to be censored from all observations still in the risk set at time \(t\).What does independence mean in this context? In competing risks, independence implies that a censored observation and an uncensored observation have the same risk of the event, regardless of the reason for censoring. In other words, by treating other failure types as censored, even if one of those other failures happens, we assume that has no impact on the time of failure for the event of interest. There is NO formal test for this. We must decide based on context of the problem. In other words, are observations with a high risk of one event equally likely to experience the other events?

Since we have multiple types of events, we will be working with a different data set. The world leaders data set was compiled by Bienen and van de Walle in 1991. It looked at primary leaders of all countries between 1960 and 1987. It recorded the number of years the leader was in power and the manner in which they lost power displayed in the pie chart below:

World Leaders Data Set

We want to try and build a survival analysis model for the tenure of world leaders and use the following variables to measure their impact.

Estimation

Remember, there are two major functions in survival analysis:

  • Survival function - probability of surviving beyond time \(t\)

\[ S(t) = P(T>t)=1-F(t) \]

  • Hazard function - conditional failure rate in an interval:

\[ h(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \rightarrow 0} \frac{P(t<T<t+\Delta t | T>t)}{\Delta t} \]

When there are multiple event types, the hazard function contains two variables - \(T\) and \(J\). Here, \(J\) is the type of event. The cause/specific hazard function is as follows:

\[ h_{i,j}(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \rightarrow 0} \frac{P(t<T_i<t+\Delta t, J_i=j | T_i>t)}{\Delta t} \] THe interpretation stays the same, just it is now type specific. The total hazard for an observation \(i\) is then just the sum of the type specific hazards:

\[ h_i(t)=\sum_{j} h_{i,j}(t) \]

The cumulative incidence function (CIF) is the unconditional probability that event type \(k\) occurs by time \(t\):

\[ F_k(t)=P(T\le t, K=k) \]

The probability of any event by time \(t\) is just the sum of the individual CIF’s:

\[ F(t) = \sum_k F_k (t) \]

The overall survival function is still unconditional, since survival means surviving all of the risks.

\[ S(t) = P(T>t) = 1-F(t) = 1-\sum_k F_k (t) \]

This means there is no such thing as a cause/type specific survival function.

We can estimate the CIF’s nonparametrically using the nonparametric estimates of the survival and hazard functions.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS uses PROC LIFETEST to build the CIF’s. This is the same procedure we used for developing the Kaplan-Meier estimates of the survival curve. The options are relatively the same as before as well. The plots = cif(CL) option provides a graphical representation of the CIF. The conftype = loglog option specifies the needed loglog transformation to obtain the confidence interval estimates for the CIF. The error = delta option speficies the delta variance method of the CIF estimator. The time statement is as before where we have the two pieces of our target variable - the tenure and the censor flag. The failcode option specifies the event type we are interested in. Here we are just looking at the event type 1 - constitutional removal from power.

proc lifetest data=Survival.leaders plots=cif(CL) conftype=loglog error=delta;
    time years*lost(0) / failcode=1;
    format lost lost.;
run;

To view the three CIF’s for our data’s three event types, the code below changes the previous failcode option to now include all three event types 1, 2, and 3.
