R

R uses the finegray function to help build the CIF’s in the survfit function. The structure is a little different than previous functions. The first thing we define is our Surv object in the finegray function. This function will structure our data into the proper competing risks format to calculate our CIF’s. We need our data to have a start time, stop time, and event status to calculate the CIF’s in the survfit function. The etype = option specifies the event type of interest to construct the CIF around.

Next, we input the new data objects into their own survfit functions. The Surv object still defines the target variable, now in three pieces - start, stop, and event status. We are not stratifying our results so we use the ~ 1 formula instead of inputting any variables. The data = option defines our finegray data set and the weight = option defines any weights created in the finegray function.

Now we have our three CIF’s. We combine them into a list to then plot in the ggsurvplot function.

lcon_data <- finegray(Surv(years, lost) ~ .,
                      data = leaders, etype = "Constitutional")
lnat_data <- finegray(Surv(years, lost) ~ .,
                      data = leaders, etype = "Natural")
lnon_data <- finegray(Surv(years, lost) ~ .,
                      data = leaders, etype = "Non-Constitutional")

lcon <- survfit(Surv(fgstart, fgstop, fgstatus) ~ 1,
                data = lcon_data, weight = fgwt)
lnat <- survfit(Surv(fgstart, fgstop, fgstatus) ~ 1,
                data = lnat_data, weight = fgwt)
lnon <- survfit(Surv(fgstart, fgstop, fgstatus) ~ 1,
                data = lnon_data, weight = fgwt)

leadlist <- list(constitutional = lcon, natural = lnat, nonconstitutional = lnon)

Cause-Specific Hazard Model

Type specific events can be modeled with both proportional hazard models and accelerated failure time models.

Typically, the modeling approach for competing risks is the use separate Cox regression models for each type of event, treating all other events as censored. Essentially, we are modeling the effects of predictors on the cause-specific hazard instead of the overall hazard.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

We still use the exact same structure to modeling our type specific hazards as we did for our overall hazards in the Cox regression model section of the notes. PROC PHREG will build the model of the leaders data set. The class statement is used for our region categorical variable. The model statement contains both pieces of our target variable on the left hand side of the equal sign. The only difference is that we have many different values for the lost variable that are censored. Here the values of 0 (still in power), 1 (constitutionally removed), and 3 (non-constitutionally removed) are all censor events for leaving due to natural causes. The remainder of the procedure is like we have defined before.

Conditional Processes

The competing risks approach presumes that each event type has its own hazard that governs both the occurrence and timing of events of that type. They are assumed to be independent processes acting in parallel with each other. For example, death due to natural causes vs. forcible removal from power in our leaders data set.

In a business setting, this independence assumption rarely seems reasonable. For example, consider the event to be buying a personal computer. There are two types of computer you are potentially buying - an Apple or a Mac. There are not two independent processes where we see what happens first. One process governs when you will buy a computer, while another process determines the choice of the computer. Conditional processes occur when these events are not independent of each other and are conditional on each other. There are two common approaches to conditional process modeling:

  1. Two-Stage Modeling
  2. Fine-Gray Model

Two-Stage Modeling

Two-stage modeling is a rather straight-forward approach. You model each of the stages (time and event) separately.

  1. Survival analysis - when will any event occur
  2. Classification model - what ype of event occurs

From our previous example of buying a computer, we would build a survival analysis to determine when we would buy another computer and a classification model (say logistic regression) on which type of computer we would buy.

Fine-Gray Model

The Fine-Gray approach to modeling conditional processes focuses on modeling sub-hazards. By treating non-\(k\) events as censored, in Cox regression modeling, you are modeling the cause-specific hazard:

\[ h_{k} (t) = -\frac{d}{dt}\log (1-F(t)) \] which the the rate of event \(k\) for those still at risk at time \(t\) conditional on no event happening yet.

Instead, we could take the CIF’s and look at the sub-hazard:

\[ h^*_{k} (t) = -\frac{d}{dt}\log (1-F_k (t)) \] which is the rate of event \(k\) for those still at risk at time \(t\) conditional on event \(k\) not happening yet.

The Fine-Gray model replaces the cause-specific hazard with the sub-hazard to get a proportional sub-hazard model:

\[ \log h^*_k (t)=\log h^*_{0,k} (t) + \beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k} \]

By using the CIF’s rather than the overall survival function (using \(1-F_k(t)\) instead of \(1-F(t)\)), the risk set is adjusted to account for different events happening. Risks are essentially balanced by looking at the probability of one specific event type in the presence of other event types by keeping failures from other causes “at risk” for the particular event type we are focused on. In other words, the other events are still competing risks and not truly treated as censored. This makes your conclusions conditionally focused on the event of interest.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

PROC PHREG in SAS will still give us the needed functionality. Instead of flagging events that are not being modeled as censored, the censor variable only makes observations that are truly censored and have yet to experience any event. The main difference is the eventcode = option where we specify the event of interest. This informs SAS that we want to build the Fine-Gray model for event type 2 (natural causes) while leaving the other events as still competing, but now conditional.

ods select html FitStatistics ConvergenceStatus ParameterEstimates;

    class region;
    model years*lost(0) = manner start military age conflict loginc growth pop land literacy region / ties=efron rl eventcode=2;

Repeated Events

Previous sections have analyzed time to a single event and time to one of many types of events. Let’s extend this again to the possibility of multiple occurrences of a single event. Repeated events, like competing risks, is a particular type of multi-state analysis that builds upon the previous things we have learned. For some situations/data, it may be informative to consider the event of interest happening more than once:

  • Repairs to a machine
  • Hospital readmissions
  • Defaults on loans

Most techniques are the same, however, the independence of observations no longer applies since an observation can potentially contribute multiple events to the data set.

Since we have repeated events, we will be working with a different data set. The bladder tumors data set was compiled by Andrews and Hertzberg in 1985. It looked at a randomized trial of 85 patients and counted the number of recurrences of bladder tumors. The distribution of the repeated event of bladder tumors is in the pie chart below:

Bladder Tumors Data Set

We want to try and build a survival analysis model for the time until recurrence using the following data:

World Leaders Data Dictionary
Variable Description
Start either a 0 or time of previous recurrence (in months)
Stop current recurrence time (or time of censoring)
Event tumor recurrence during the observed start, stop time period (in months)
ID patient ID
rx placebo (1) or treatment (2) group
number number of tumors initially present (truncated at 8)
size diameter (cm) of largest initial tumor
enum # of previous times with tumors (up to max of 4)

Intensity Process

There are multiple modeling choices with repeated events. Each modeling choice will end up answering a different question. You must then consider what questions you are trying to answer. - How do you want to treat repeated events? - Is the order of events important? - Are additional events indicative of a more serious issue? - What is the time scale you are interested in? - Time to the event? - Time between events?

In repeated events, the hazard function is called the intesity process:

\[ h_i(t) = y_i(t) h_0(t) e^{\beta_1 x_{i,1} + \cdots + \beta_k x_{i,k}} \] where \(y_i(t)\) is an indicator for being in the risk set at time \(t\). All previous models implied that \(y_i(t) = 1\) for an observation’s entire tenure in the data set. The questions asked above help determine the value of \(y_i(t)\). This helps us determine who is in the risk set, when they are in the risk set, and which risk set they are in.

Models for Repeated Events

There are two main approaches to modeling repeated events:

  1. Independence model
  2. Conditional model

Each of these two approaches has different variations that we will discuss below.

Independence Model

The easiest approach is modeling the recurrences as separate, independent events. This approach assumes that all recurrences are identical. Essentially, the risk of the event is the same regardless of the numebr of previous events. The main focus here is the overall effect, ignoring the order of type of recurrence. In this approach, our data is structured so that each observation has time intervals of (start, \(1^{st}\)}], (\(1^{st}\), \(2^{nd}\)], …, (\(k^{th}\), stop]. This means that the same observation (with repeated events) appears multiple times in your data set. However, we know that these observations are not truly independent of each other. There are two different approaches to account for this in our modeling:

  1. Time-Dependent Variables
  2. Robust Standard Errors

Time-Dependent Variables

For the time-dependent variable approach we use the same counting process data structure that we mentioned in the Cox regression model section above. In the counting process data structure, we had a separate observation for each individual when their time-dependent variable changed. Now this time-dependent variable is just our count of previous events! For each event, our time-dependent variable of previous event count increases for each “new” observation (or row) in our data set. Here we just think of these observations as independent, “different” observations as they have a changed history - the number of previous events.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

In SAS we model this Cox regression model in the same fashion as we have done before. Since we are assuming that the previous event count (enum) signifies a “new” observation, we just build the model on the counting process data set. All the previous functionality as defined before is the same here.

ods select html FitStatistics ConvergenceStatus ParameterEstimates;
proc phreg data=Survival.Bladder;
    model (start, stop)*event(0) = rx number size enum / ties=efron;
run;

Robust Standard Errors

There is still the possibility that time-dependent variables might not explain away all of the possible correlation between observations. The set-up to the robust standard error approach is the same as the time-dependent variables. For the time-dependent variable approach we use the same counting process data structure that we mentioned in the Cox regression model section above. In the counting process data structure, we had a separate observation for each individual when their time-dependent variable changed. Now this time-dependent variable is just our count of previous events! For each event, our time-dependent variable of previous event count increases for each “new” observation (or row) in our data set. However, we assume that there might still be some correlation between observations that come from the same original subject. We account for this correlation by adjusting our standard errors with the robust sandwich estimate which calculates the covariances for our parameter estimates from a correlation matrix that doesn’t assume independence.

Let’s see how to do this in each of our softwares!

SAS

In PROC PHREG, The covs(aggregate) option specifies this technique. The id statement followed by the variable that signifies the unique subjects let’s SAS know which observations are “grouped” together.

ods select html FitStatistics ConvergenceStatus ParameterEstimates;
proc phreg data=Survival.Bladder covs(aggregate);
    model (start, stop)*event(0) = rx number size enum / ties=efron;
    id id;
run;

Conditional Model

Unlike the independence model, we can preserve the ordering of events if it is important. In the conditional set of models, we stratify on the number of events, so only those who have had a previous event are in the risk set for the next one. For example, an observation is not in the risk set for the third event until it has the second event.

This means that we subset our original data set down into smaller pieces. We will have a data set for those observations who have had at most one event, at least one event and at most two events, at least two events and at most three events, etc. Our softwares will split these data sets for us so we do not have to. Each recurrence is a separate stratum (essentially its own model) with its own baseline hazard function. There is no estimates/inferences on the number of recurrences since they are in a separate data set and model.

In this setup, there are two approaches to account for interpretation of time:

  1. Full Time Model
  2. Gap Time Model

Full Time Model

with the conditional model under the full time specification, each event’s start time is determined by the previous event’s stop time. For example, if an observation had its first event at time 6 and a second event at time 10, then the first observation would start at 0 and stop at 6. The second observation would start at 6 and stop at 10. In the full time model, the hazard ratio and interpretation of the coefficients is the effect of the \(k^{th}\) event since entry time. It would probably be easier to understand this through an example.

Let’s see this approach in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS can either assume that each model has the same coefficients (effects of the variables) or differing ones across strata. First, let’s see how to code the same coefficients across each model. The only difference in this code as compared to the previous COx regression models is the strata statement. Here we specify the variable that will effectively split our data set into smaller pieces. The enum variable does that for us in our data set.

ods select html FitStatistics ConvergenceStatus ParameterEstimates;

To get SAS to treat each strata separately in terms of coefficients on parameters, we need to create “interactions” for each of our variables with the different values of our stratification variable enum. Now SAS will estimate different coefficients for each stratum’s model.

Gap Time Model

Notice with the conditional model under the full time specification, each event’s start time is determined by the previous event’s stop time. An alternative time scale is the gap time where we choose to model the time since last event. In gap-time models, time is reset to 0 after each event, so the time until the prior event has no bearing on the current event’s risk set. In the full time model, the hazard ratio and interpretation of the coefficients is the effect of the \(k^{th}\) event since entry time. It would probably be easier to understand this through an example. For example, if an observation had its first event at time 6 and a second event at time 10, then the first observation would start at 0 and stop at 6. The second observation would start at 0 and stop at 4. It would probably be easier to understand this through an example.

Let’s see this approach in each of our softwares!

SAS

SAS can either assume that each model has the same coefficients (effects of the variables) or differing ones across strata (similar to the full time approach). First, let’s see how to code the same coefficients across each model. First, we need to calculate the gap time as done here in the DATA step. We subtract the start and stop time for each of our observations, effectively reseting the timer at each instance. The only difference in this modeling code as compared to the previous COx regression models is the strata statement. Here we specify the variable that will effectively split our data set into smaller pieces. The enum variable does that for us in our data set.

Let’s examine the above results. When assuming that each model has different coefficients, it doesn’t appear as anything really is statistically significant in terms of the three variables except for two - the number variable in our first model and in our fourth model. Let’s take this number variable in the first model (the one with the lowest p-value) and interpret it to help our understanding. The interpretation is easiest with the transformation introduced in the Cox regression section of the notes. For each number of original tumors found, the rate of getting a recurrence increases 26.9% (\(= (e^{0.23824}-1)\times 100\)) from the time of previous event. That last piece is key. This interpretation goes from the time of this individual’s previous event until their first (current) event.
